[0.003, "o", "\u001b[41;10H\u001b[30m\u001b[103m4\u001b[43;7H4\u001b[44;11H4\u001b[51;4H4\u001b[66;223H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f41,10\u001b[67;3H\u001b[?25h"]
[0.242, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001b[m\u000f0"]
[0.003, "o", "\u001b[1;2H number of beacons between DTIMs (1 = every beacon includes DTIM element)\u001b[5X\u001b[2;3H(default: 2)\u001b[37X\r\ndtim_period=2\r\n\u001b[71X\u001b[5;3HMaximum number of stations allowed in station table. New stations will be  \u001b[6;3Hrejected after the station table is full. IEEE 802.11 has a limit of 2007  \u001b[7;3Hdifferent association IDs, so this number should not be larger than that.\r\n# (default: 2007)\r\nmax_num_sta=255\r\n\u001b[65X\u001b[11;3HRTS/CTS threshold; -1 = disabled (default); range -1..65535\u001b[10X\u001b[12;3HIf this field is not included in hostapd.conf, hostapd will not control   \u001b[13;3HRTS threshold and 'iwconfig wlan# rts <val>' can be used to set it.\u001b[7X\r\nrts_threshold=-1\u001b[59X\r\n\u001b[45X\u001b[16;2H Fragmentation threshold; -1 = disabled (default); range -1, 256..2346\u001b[17;3HIf this field is not included in hostapd.conf, hostapd will not control  \u001b[18;3Hfragmentation threshold and 'iwconfig wlan# frag <val>' can be used to set   \u001b[19;3Hit.\u001b[66X\r\nfragm_threshold=-1\u001b[10X\r\n\u001b[11X\n# Rate configuration\u001b[23;4Hefault is to enable all rates supported by the hardware. This configuration\u001b[24;3Hitem allows this list be filtered so that only the listed rates will be left\u001b[25;3Hin the list. If the list is empty, all rates are used. This list can have  \u001b[26;3Hentries that are not in the list of rates the hardware supports (such entries\u001b[27;3Hare ignored). The entries in this list are in 100 kbps, i.e., 11 Mbps = 110.\r\n# If this item is present, at least one rate have to be matching with the rates\u001b[29;3Hhardware supports.\u001b[46X\u001b[30;4Hefault: use the most common supported rate setting for the selected\r\n# hw_mode (i.e., this line can be removed from configuration file in most\u001b[32;3Hcases)\u001b[28X\u001b[33;2Hsupported_rates=10 20 55 110 60 90 120 180 2\u001b[30m\u001b[103m40\u001b[m\u000f 360 480 5\u001b[30m\u001b[103m40\u001b[m\u000f\r\n\u001b[69X\u001b[35;3HBasic rate set configuration\u001b[36;2H List of rates (in 100 kbps) that are included in the basic rate set.\u001b[37;3HIf this item is not included, usually reasonable default set is used.  \u001b[38;2Hbasic_rates=10 20\u001b[39;2Hbasic_rates=10 20 55 110\u001b[40;2Hbasic_rates=60 120 2\u001b[30m\u001b[103m40\u001b[m\u000f  \r\n\u001b[20X\u001b[42;3HBeacon frame TX rate configuration\u001b[43;3HThis sets the TX rate that is used to transmit Beacon frames. If this item is\u001b[44;3Hnot included, the driver default rate (likely lowest rate) is used.\u001b[45;2H Legacy (CCK/OFDM rates):\u001b[46;3H   beacon_rate=<legacy rate in 100 kbps> \u001b[47;3HHT:\u001b[19X\u001b[48;4H  beacon_rate=ht:<HT MCS>\u001b[49;3HVHT:\u001b[23X\u001b[50;4H  beacon_rate=vht:<VHT MCS>\u001b[51;3HHE:\u001b[9X\u001b[52;2H    beacon_rate=he:<HE MCS>\r\n#\u001b[15X\r\n# For example, beacon_rate=10 for 1 Mbps or beacon_rate=60 for 6 Mbps (OFDM).\r\n#beacon_rate=10 \r\n\u001b[21X\n# Short Preamble\u001b[58;3HThis parameter can be used to enable optional use of short preamble for\u001b[59;3Hframes sent at 2 Mbps, 5.5 Mbps, and 11 Mbps to improve network performance. \u001b[60;3HThis applies only to IEEE 802.11b-compatible networks and this should only be\u001b[61;3Henabled if the local hardware supports use of short preamble. If any of the \u001b[62;3Hassociated STAs do not support short preamble, use of short preamble will be\u001b[63;3Hdisabled (and enabled when such STAs disassociate) dynamically.\u001b[64;3H0 = do not allow use of short preamble (default)\u001b[21X\u001b[65;3H1 = allow use of short preamble\u001b[29X\u001b[66;223H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f278,46          7%\u001b[67;4H\u001b[?25h"]
[0.934, "o", "\u001b[?25l\b\u001b[m\u000f \b"]
[0.003, "o", "\u001b[1;2H#### hostapd configuration file ##############################################\u001b[2;3HEmpty lines and lines starting with # are ignored\r\n\u001b[13X\n# AP netdevice name (without 'ap' postfix, i.e., wlan0 uses wlan0ap for\u001b[5;3Hmanagement frames with the Host AP driver); wlan0 with many nl80211 drivers\u001b[6;3HNote: This attribute can be overridden by the values supplied with the '-i'\u001b[7;3Hcommand line parameter.\u001b[50X\r\ninterface=wlan0  \r\n\u001b[15X\n# In case of atheros and nl80211 driver interfaces, an additional\u001b[11;3Hconfiguration parameter, bridge, may be used to notify hostapd if the\u001b[12;3Hinterface is included in a bridge. This parameter is not used with Host AP\u001b[13;3Hdriver. If the bridge parameter is not set, the drivers will automatically\r\n# figure out the bridge interface (assuming sysfs is enabled and mounted to\r\n# /sys) and this parameter may not be needed.\u001b[16;2H\u001b[70X\u001b[17;3HFor nl80211, this parameter can be used to request the AP interface to be\u001b[18;3Hadded to the bridge automatically (brctl may refuse to do this before hostapd\u001b[19;3Hhas been started to change the interface mode). If needed, the bridge\r\n# interface is also created.\r\n#bridge=br0\r\n\u001b[20X\u001b[23;4Hriver interface type (hostap/wired/none/nl80211/bsd);\u001b[22X\u001b[24;3Hdefault: hostap). nl80211 is used with all Linux mac80211 drivers.\u001b[10X\u001b[25;3HUse driver=none if building hostapd as a standalone RADIUS server that does\u001b[26;3Hnot control any wireless/wired driver.\u001b[39X\u001b[27;3Hdriver=hostap\u001b[63X\r\n\u001b[79X\u001b[29;3HDriver interface parameters (mainly for development testing use)\u001b[30;4Hriver_params=<params>\u001b[46X\r\n\u001b[73X\u001b[32;3Hhostapd event logger configuration\u001b[33;2H\u001b[58X\r\n# Two output method: syslog and stdout (only usable if not forking to\u001b[35;3Hbackground).\u001b[16X\u001b[36;2H\u001b[69X\u001b[37;3HModule bitfield (ORed bitfield of modules that will be logged; -1 = all\u001b[38;2H modules):\u001b[7X\u001b[39;2H bit 0 (1) = IEEE 802.11\u001b[40;2H bit 1 (2) = IEEE 802.1X\r\n# bit 2 (\u001b[30m\u001b[103m4\u001b[m\u000f) = RADIUS\u001b[42;3Hbit 3 (8) = WPA\u001b[19X\u001b[43;3Hbit \u001b[30m\u001b[103m4\u001b[m\u000f (16) = driver interface\u001b[48X\u001b[44;3Hbit 6 (6\u001b[30m\u001b[103m4\u001b[m\u000f) = MLME\u001b[50X\u001b[45;2H\u001b[25X\u001b[46;3HLevels (minimum value for logged events):\u001b[47;3H 0 = verbose debugging\u001b[48;4H1 = debugging\u001b[12X\u001b[49;3H 2 = informational messages\u001b[50;4H3 = notification\u001b[11X\u001b[51;3H \u001b[30m\u001b[103m4\u001b[m\u000f = warning\u001b[52;2H\u001b[27X\r\nlogger_syslog=-1\r\nlogger_syslog_level=2\u001b[56X\r\nlogger_stdout=-1\r\nlogger_stdout_level=2\r\n\u001b[16X\u001b[58;3HInterface for separate control program. If this is specified, hostapd  \u001b[59;3Hwill create this directory and a UNIX domain socket for listening to requests\u001b[60;3Hfrom external programs (CLI/GUI, etc.) for status information and\u001b[12X\u001b[61;3Hconfiguration. The socket file will be named based on the interface name, so\u001b[62;3Hmultiple hostapd processes/interfaces can be run at the same time if more   \u001b[63;3Hthan one interface is used.\u001b[36X\u001b[64;3H/run/hostapd is the recommended directory for sockets and by default,\u001b[65;3Hhostapd_cli will use it when trying to connect with hostapd.\u001b[66;223H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f41,10          Top\u001b[67;3H\u001b[?25h"]
[0.265, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001b[m\u000f3"]
[0.003, "o", "\u001b[1;2H driver) on each available channel for given hw_mode. Increasing this value   \u001b[2;3Hmeans sacrificing startup time and gathering more data wrt channel\r\n# interference that may help choosing a better channel. This can also help fine\u001b[4;3Htune the ACS scan time in case a driver has different scan dwell times.\u001b[5;2H\u001b[76X\u001b[6;3Hacs_chan_bias is a space-separated list of <channel>:<bias> pairs. It can be\u001b[7;3Hused to increase (or decrease) the likelihood of a specific channel to be\r\n# selected by the ACS algorithm. The total interference factor for each channel\r\n# gets multiplied by the specified bias value before finding the channel with\u001b[10;3Hthe lowest value. In other words, values between 0.0 and 1.0 can be used to\u001b[11;3Hmake a channel more likely to be picked while values larger than 1.0 make the\u001b[12;3Hspecified channel less likely to be picked. This can be used, e.g., to prefer\u001b[13;3Hthe commonly used 2.4 GHz band channels 1, 6, and 11 (which is the default\u001b[14;3Hbehavior on 2.4 GHz band if no acs_chan_bias parameter is specified).    \u001b[15;2H\u001b[44X\n Defaults:\u001b[17;2Hacs_num_scans=5\u001b[59X\u001b[18;2Hacs_chan_bias=1:0.8 6:0.8 11:0.8\u001b[46X\r\n\u001b[71X\u001b[20;3HChannel list restriction. This option allows hostapd to select one of the\u001b[21;2H provided channels when a channel should be automatically selected.\r\n# Channel list can be provided as range using hyphen ('-') or individual\u001b[23;3Hchannels can be specified by space (' ') separated values\u001b[24;3HDefault: all channels allowed in selected hw_mode\u001b[17X\u001b[25;2Hchanlist=100 104 108 112 116\u001b[48X\u001b[26;2Hchanlist=1 6 11-13\u001b[21X\r\n\u001b[15X\n# Frequency list restriction. This option allows hostapd to select one of the\u001b[29;3Hprovided frequencies when a frequency should be automatically selected.\u001b[30;3HFrequency list can be provided as range using hyphen ('-') or individual\r\n# frequencies can be specified by comma (',') separated values\u001b[32;3HDefault: all frequencies allowed in selected hw_mode\u001b[33;2Hfreqlist=2\u001b[30m\u001b[103m43\u001b[m\u000f7,5955,5975\u001b[34;2Hfreqlist=2\u001b[30m\u001b[103m43\u001b[m\u000f7,5985-6105\u001b[45X\r\n\u001b[14X\u001b[36;2H Exclude DFS channels from ACS\u001b[37;3HThis option can be used to exclude all DFS channels from the ACS channel list\u001b[38;3Hin cases where the driver supports DFS channels.\u001b[39;2Hacs_exclude_dfs=1\u001b[7X\r\n\u001b[25X\u001b[41;3HInclude only preferred scan channels from 6 GHz band for ACS\u001b[42;3HThis option can be used to include only preferred scan channels in the 6 GHz\u001b[43;4Hand. This can be useful in particular for devices that operate only a 6 GHz\u001b[44;3HBSS without a collocated 2.4/5 GHz BSS.\u001b[45;2H Default behavior is to include all PSC and non-PSC channels.\u001b[46;2Hacs_exclude_6ghz_non_psc=1\u001b[16X\r\n\u001b[24X\u001b[48;3HEnable background radar feature\u001b[49;3HThis feature allows CAC to be run on dedicated radio RF chains while the\u001b[50;3Hradio(s) are otherwise running normal AP activities on other channels.\u001b[51;3HThis requires that the driver and the radio support it before feature will\u001b[52;2H actually be enabled, i.e., this parameter value is ignored with drivers that\r\n# do not advertise support for the capability.\r\n# 0: Leave disabled (default)\r\n# 1: Enable it. \r\n#enable_background_radar=1\u001b[58;3HSet minimum permitted max TX power (in dBm) for ACS and DFS channel selection.\u001b[59;3H(default 0, i.e., not constraint)\u001b[44X\u001b[60;2Hmin_tx_power=20\u001b[51X\r\n\u001b[78X\u001b[62;3HBeacon interval in kus (1.024 ms) (default: 100; range 15..65535)\u001b[8X\r\nbeacon_int=100\u001b[15X\r\n\u001b[71X\u001b[65;3HDTIM (delivery traffic information message) period (range 1..255):\u001b[66;223H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f213,12          5%\u001b[67;4H\u001b[?25h"]
[0.247, "o", "\u001b[?25l\b\u001b[m\u000f \b"]
[0.002, "o", "\u001b[1;2H#### hostapd configuration file ##############################################\u001b[2;3HEmpty lines and lines starting with # are ignored\u001b[17X\r\n\u001b[79X\u001b[4;3HAP netdevice name (without 'ap' postfix, i.e., wlan0 uses wlan0ap for  \u001b[5;2H management frames with the Host AP driver); wlan0 with many nl80211 drivers\u001b[6;3HNote: This attribute can be overridden by the values supplied with the '-i' \u001b[7;3Hcommand line parameter.\u001b[50X\r\ninterface=wlan0\u001b[64X\r\n\u001b[77X\u001b[10;3HIn case of atheros and nl80211 driver interfaces, an additional\u001b[12X\u001b[11;3Hconfiguration parameter, bridge, may be used to notify hostapd if the\u001b[8X\u001b[12;3Hinterface is included in a bridge. This parameter is not used with Host AP   \u001b[13;3Hdriver. If the bridge parameter is not set, the drivers will automatically\u001b[14;3Hfigure out the bridge interface (assuming sysfs is enabled and mounted to\u001b[15;2H /sys) and this parameter may not be needed.\u001b[16;2H\u001b[10X\n For nl80211, this parameter can be used to request the AP interface to be\u001b[18;2H added to the bridge automatically (brctl may refuse to do this before hostapd\r\n# has been started to change the interface mode). If needed, the bridge\u001b[20;3Hinterface is also created.\u001b[47X\u001b[21;2Hbridge=br0\u001b[57X\r\n\u001b[72X\u001b[23;3HDriver interface type (hostap/wired/none/nl80211/bsd);   \u001b[24;3Hdefault: hostap). nl80211 is used with all Linux mac80211 drivers.\u001b[25;2H Use driver=none if building hostapd as a standalone RADIUS server that does\u001b[26;2H not control any wireless/wired driver.\r\n# driver=hostap\r\n\u001b[77X\u001b[29;3HDriver interface parameters (mainly for development testing use)\u001b[7X\u001b[30;3Hdriver_params=<params>\u001b[50X\r\n\u001b[62X\u001b[32;3Hhostapd event logger configuration\u001b[18X\u001b[33;2H\u001b[23X\n Two output method: syslog and stdout (only usable if not forking to\r\n# background).\u001b[36;2H\u001b[30X\u001b[37;3HModule bitfield (ORed bitfield of modules that will be logged; -1 = all\u001b[6X\u001b[38;3Hmodules):\u001b[39X\u001b[39;2H bit 0 (1) = IEEE 802.11\r\n# bit 1 (2) = IEEE 802.1X\u001b[41;3Hbit 2 (\u001b[30m\u001b[103m4\u001b[m\u000f) = RADIUS\u001b[42X\u001b[42;3Hbit 3 (8) = WPA\u001b[61X\u001b[43;4Hit \u001b[30m\u001b[103m4\u001b[m\u000f (16) = driver interface\u001b[47X\u001b[44;3Hbit 6 (6\u001b[30m\u001b[103m4\u001b[m\u000f) = MLME\u001b[22X\u001b[45;2H\u001b[61X\n Levels (minimum value for logged events):\r\n#  0 = verbose debugging\u001b[48;3H 1 = debugging\u001b[17X\u001b[49;3H 2 = informational messages\u001b[45X\u001b[50;3H 3 = notification\u001b[53X\u001b[51;3H \u001b[30m\u001b[103m4\u001b[m\u000f = warning\u001b[62X\u001b[52;2H\u001b[77X\r\nlogger_syslog=-1\u001b[30X\r\nlogger_syslog_level=2\u001b[8X\r\nlogger_stdout=-1\r\nlogger_stdout_level=2\u001b[5X\u001b[58;3HInterface for separate control program. If this is specified, hostapd\u001b[9X\u001b[59;3Hwill create this directory and a UNIX domain socket for listening to requests\u001b[60;2H from external programs (CLI/GUI, etc.) for status information and\r\n# configuration. The socket file will be named based on the interface name, so\u001b[62;3Hmultiple hostapd processes/interfaces can be run at the same time if more\r\n# than one interface is used.\r\n# /run/hostapd is the recommended directory for sockets and by default,\u001b[65;3Hhostapd_cli will use it when trying to connect with hostapd.\u001b[6X\u001b[66;223H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f41,10          Top\u001b[67;3H\u001b[?25h"]
[0.183, "o", "\u001b[?25l\b\u001b[m\u000f \u001b[41;10H4\u001b[43;7H4\u001b[44;11H4\u001b[51;4H4\u001b[66;223H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f1,1  \u001b[67;2H\u001b[?25h"]
[0.165, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001b[m\u000f3"]
[0.002, "o", "\u001b[42;7H\u001b[30m\u001b[103m3\u001b[50;4H3\u001b[66;223H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f42,7\u001b[67;3H\u001b[?25h"]
[0.098, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001b[m\u000f0"]
[0.003, "o", "\u001b[1;2Hdeny_mac_file=/etc/hostapd/hostapd.deny\u001b[39X\r\n\u001b[51X\n# IEEE 802.11 specifies two authentication algorithms. hostapd can be\u001b[4;3Hconfigured to allow both of these or only one. Open system authentication\u001b[5;3Hshould be used with IEEE 802.1X.\u001b[43X\u001b[6;3HBit fields of allowed authentication algorithms:\u001b[27X\u001b[7;3Hbit 0 = Open System Authentication\r\n# bit 1 = Shared Key Authentication (requires WEP)\r\nauth_algs=3\r\n\u001b[65X\u001b[11;3HSend empty SSID in beacons and ignore probe request frames that do not\u001b[12;3Hspecify full SSID, i.e., require stations to know SSID.\u001b[19X\u001b[13;4Hefault: disabled (0)\u001b[53X\u001b[14;3H1 = send empty (length=0) SSID in beacon and ignore probe request for    \u001b[15;3H    broadcast SSID\u001b[25X\u001b[16;2H 2 = clear SSID (ASCII 0), but keep the original length (this may be required\u001b[17;3H    with some clients that do not support empty SSID) and ignore probe   \u001b[18;3H    requests for broadcast SSID\u001b[46X\r\nignore_broadcast_ssid=0\u001b[48X\r\n\u001b[28X\u001b[21;2H Do not reply to broadcast Probe Request frames from unassociated STA if there\r\n# is no room for additional stations (max_num_sta). This can be used to\u001b[23;3Hdiscourage a STA from trying to associate with this AP if the association\u001b[24;3Hwould be rejected due to maximum STA limit.\u001b[23X\u001b[25;3HDefault: 0 (disabled)\u001b[54X\u001b[26;2Hno_probe_resp_if_max_sta=0\u001b[13X\r\n\u001b[15X\n# Additional vendor specific elements for Beacon and Probe Response frames\u001b[29;3HThis parameter can be used to add additional vendor specific element(s) into\u001b[30;3Hthe end of the Beacon and Probe Response frames. The format for these\r\n# element(s) is a hexdump of the raw information elements (id+len+payload for\u001b[32;3Hone or more elements)\u001b[13X\u001b[33;2Hvendor_elements=dd0411223\u001b[30m\u001b[103m30\u001b[m\u000f1\r\n\u001b[69X\u001b[35;3HAdditional vendor specific elements for (Re)Association Response frames\u001b[36;2H This parameter can be used to add additional vendor specific element(s) into\u001b[37;3Hthe end of the (Re)Association Response frames. The format for these   \u001b[38;3Helement(s) is a hexdump of the raw information elements (id+len+payload for\u001b[39;3Hone or more elements)  \u001b[40;2Hassocresp_elements=dd0411223\u001b[30m\u001b[103m30\u001b[m\u000f1\r\n\u001b[20X\u001b[42;3HTX queue parameters (EDCF / bursting)\u001b[43;3Htx_queue_<queue name>_<param>\u001b[44;3Hqueues: data0, data1, data2, data3\u001b[45;2H               (data0 is the highest priority queue)\u001b[46;3Hparameters:\u001b[30X\u001b[47;4H aifs: AIFS (default 2)\u001b[48;4H cwmin: cwMin (1, 3, 7, 15, 31, 63, 127, 255, 511, 1023, 2047, 4095, 8191,\u001b[49;4H        16383, 32767)\u001b[5X\u001b[50;4H cwmax: cwMax (same values as cwMin, cwMax >= cwMin)\u001b[51;4H burst: maximum length (in milliseconds with precision of up to 0.1 ms) for\u001b[52;2H          bursting\r\n#\u001b[15X\r\n# Default WMM parameters (IEEE 802.11 draft; 11-03-0504-03-000e):\r\n# These parameters are used by the access point when transmitting frames\r\n# to the clients.    \r\n#\u001b[58;3HLow priority / AC_BK = background\u001b[36X\u001b[59;2Htx_queue_data3_aifs=7\u001b[57X\u001b[60;2Htx_queue_data3_cwmin=15\u001b[43X\u001b[61;2Htx_queue_data3_cwmax=1023\u001b[52X\u001b[62;2Htx_queue_data3_burst=0\u001b[52X\u001b[63;3HNote: for IEEE 802.11b mode: cWmin=31 cWmax=1023 burst=0\u001b[64;2H\u001b[70X\u001b[65;3HNormal priority / AC_BE = best effort\u001b[23X\u001b[66;223H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f358,27          9%\u001b[67;4H\u001b[?25h"]
[0.130, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001b[m\u000f0"]
[0.002, "o", "\u001b[1;2H Static WEP key configuration\u001b[10X\r\n#\u001b[3;3HThe key number to use when transmitting.\u001b[27X\u001b[4;3HIt must be between 0 and 3, and the corresponding key must be set.\u001b[7X\u001b[5;3Hdefault: not set\u001b[16X\u001b[6;2Hwep_default_key=0\u001b[32X\u001b[7;3HThe WEP keys to use.\u001b[14X\u001b[8;3HA key may be a quoted string or unquoted hexadecimal digits.\r\n# The key length should be 5, 13, or 16 characters, or 10, 26, or 32\r\n# digits, depending on whether 40-bit (64-bit), 104-bit (128-bit), or\u001b[11;3H128-bit (152-bit) WEP is used.\u001b[40X\u001b[12;3HOnly the default key must be supplied; the others are optional.\u001b[13;12Hnot set\u001b[5X\u001b[14;2Hwep_key0=123456789a\u001b[51X\u001b[15;2Hwep_key1=\"vwxyz\"   \u001b[16;2Hwep_key2=0102030405060708090a0b0c0d\u001b[42X\u001b[17;2Hwep_key3=\".2.4.6.8.0.23\"\u001b[47X\r\n\u001b[33X\n# Station inactivity limit\r\n#\u001b[21;3HIf a station does not send anything in ap_max_inactivity seconds, an\u001b[9X\u001b[22;3Hempty data frame is sent to it in order to verify whether it is\u001b[6X\u001b[23;3Hstill in range. If this frame is not ACKed, the station will be\u001b[10X\u001b[24;3Hdisassociated and then deauthenticated. This feature is used to\u001b[25;3Hclear station table of old entries when the STAs move out of the\u001b[26;2H range.\u001b[19X\r\n#\u001b[28;3HThe station can associate again with the AP if it is still in range;    \u001b[29;3Hthis inactivity poll is just used as a nicer way of verifying\u001b[15X\u001b[30;3Hinactivity; i.e., client will not report broken connection because   \u001b[31;3Hdisassociation frame is not sent immediately without first polling\u001b[9X\u001b[32;3Hthe STA with a data frame.\u001b[33;2H default: \u001b[30m\u001b[103m300\u001b[m\u000f (i.e., 5 minutes)\r\n#ap_max_inactivity=\u001b[30m\u001b[103m300\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[35;2H\u001b[72X\u001b[36;5He inactivity polling can be disabled to disconnect stations based on\u001b[6X\u001b[37;3Hinactivity timeout so that idle stations are more likely to be disconnected\u001b[38;4Hven if they are still in range of the AP. This can be done by setting\u001b[5X\u001b[39;3Hskip_inactivity_poll to 1 (default 0).\u001b[40;2Hskip_inactivity_poll=0\u001b[9X\r\n#\u001b[42;3HBSS max idle period management\u001b[7X\u001b[43;3H0 = disabled (do not advertise and manage BSS max idle period)\u001b[44;3H1 = enabled (advertise and manage BSS max idle period; default)\u001b[45;3H2 = enabled requiring protected frames (advertise and manage BSS max idle\u001b[46;3H    period and require STAs to use protected keep-alive frames)\u001b[47;2Hbss_max_idle=1\u001b[11X\u001b[48;2H\u001b[76X\u001b[49;3HMaximum acceptable BSS maximum idle period\u001b[50;3HIf this is set to a nonzero value, the AP allows STAs to request different\u001b[51;3Hmaximum idle period values. This is in the units to 1000 TUs (1.024 s)\u001b[6X\u001b[52;2Hmax_acceptable_idle_period=600\u001b[54;3HAllow STA to skip group key handshake without getting disconnection when\u001b[55;3HBSS max idle period management is enabled.\u001b[28X\u001b[56;3H0 = disconnect STA if it does not reply to group key handshake (default)\u001b[57;2H 1 = do not disconnect STA if it does not reply to group key handshake and\u001b[58;3H    if BSS max idle period management is enabled\u001b[59;2Hno_disconnect_on_group_keyerror=0\r\n\u001b[24X\u001b[61;2H Disassociate stations based on excessive transmission failures or other\u001b[62;2H indications of connection loss. This depends on the driver capabilities and\u001b[63;3Hmay not be available with all drivers.\u001b[18X\u001b[64;2Hdisassoc_low_ack=1\r\n\u001b[39X\u001b[66;223H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f517,12         14\u001b[67;5H\u001b[?25h"]
[0.265, "o", "\u001b[?25l\b\u001b[m\u000f \b"]
[0.003, "o", "\u001b[1;2Hdeny_mac_file=/etc/hostapd/hostapd.deny\r\n \u001b[3;3HIEEE 802.11 specifies two authentication algorithms. hostapd can be\u001b[4;3Hconfigured to allow both of these or only one. Open system authentication\u001b[5;3Hshould be used with IEEE 802.1X.\u001b[6;2H Bit fields of allowed authentication algorithms:\u001b[7;3Hbit 0 = Open System Authentication\u001b[8;3Hbit 1 = Shared Key Authentication (requires WEP)\u001b[12X\r\nauth_algs=3\u001b[57X\r\n\u001b[69X\u001b[11;3HSend empty SSID in beacons and ignore probe request frames that do not\u001b[12;3Hspecify full SSID, i.e., require stations to know SSID.\u001b[8X\u001b[13;12Hdisabled (0)\u001b[14;2H 1 = send empty (length=0) SSID in beacon and ignore probe request for\u001b[15;2H     broadcast SSID\u001b[16;2H 2 = clear SSID (ASCII 0), but keep the original length (this may be required\u001b[17;2H     with some clients that do not support empty SSID) and ignore probe\r\n#     requests for broadcast SSID\r\nignore_broadcast_ssid=0   \r\n \u001b[21;3HDo not reply to broadcast Probe Request frames from unassociated STA if there\u001b[22;3His no room for additional stations (max_num_sta). This can be used to\u001b[23;3Hdiscourage a STA from trying to associate with this AP if the association\u001b[24;3Hwould be rejected due to maximum STA limit.\u001b[20X\u001b[25;3HDefault: 0 (disabled)\u001b[43X\u001b[26;2Hno_probe_resp_if_max_sta=0\r\n \u001b[28;3HAdditional vendor specific elements for Beacon and Probe Response frames\u001b[29;3HThis parameter can be used to add additional vendor specific element(s) into\u001b[30;3Hthe end of the Beacon and Probe Response frames. The format for these\u001b[31;3Helement(s) is a hexdump of the raw information elements (id+len+payload for\u001b[32;3Hone or more elements)\u001b[5X\u001b[33;2Hvendor_elements=dd0411223\u001b[30m\u001b[103m30\u001b[m\u000f1   \r\n\u001b[22X\u001b[35;2H Additional vendor specific elements for (Re)Association Response frames\u001b[36;5His parameter can be used to add additional vendor specific element(s) into\u001b[37;3Hthe end of the (Re)Association Response frames. The format for these\u001b[7X\u001b[38;4Hlement(s) is a hexdump of the raw information elements (id+len+payload for\u001b[39;3Hone or more elements)\u001b[17X\u001b[40;2Hassocresp_elements=dd0411223\u001b[30m\u001b[103m30\u001b[m\u000f1\r\n \u001b[42;3HTX queue parameters (EDCF / bursting)\u001b[43;3Htx_queue_<queue name>_<param>\u001b[33X\u001b[44;3Hqueues: data0, data1, data2, data3\u001b[29X\u001b[45;3H              (data0 is the highest priority queue)\u001b[22X\u001b[46;3Hparameters:\u001b[52X\u001b[47;2H   aifs: AIFS (default 2)\u001b[48;2H   cwmin: cwMin (1, 3, 7, 15, 31, 63, 127, 255, 511, 1023, 2047, 4095, 8191,\u001b[49;3H         16383, 32767)\u001b[20X\u001b[50;3H  cwmax: cwMax (same values as cwMin, cwMax >= cwMin)\u001b[21X\u001b[51;3H  burst: maximum length (in milliseconds with precision of up to 0.1 ms) for\u001b[52;2H          bursting\u001b[12X\u001b[54;3HDefault WMM parameters (IEEE 802.11 draft; 11-03-0504-03-000e):\u001b[9X\u001b[55;3HThese parameters are used by the access point when transmitting frames\u001b[56;3Hto the clients.\u001b[57X\u001b[57;2H\u001b[74X\u001b[58;3HLow priority / AC_BK = background\u001b[15X\u001b[59;2Htx_queue_data3_aifs=7\u001b[12X\r\n#tx_queue_data3_cwmin=15\u001b[61;2Htx_queue_data3_cwmax=1023\u001b[47X\u001b[62;2Htx_queue_data3_burst=0\u001b[54X\u001b[63;3HNote: for IEEE 802.11b mode: cWmin=31 cWmax=1023 burst=0\u001b[64;2H\u001b[18X\r\n# Normal priority / AC_BE = best effort\u001b[66;223H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f358,27          9\u001b[67;4H\u001b[?25h"]
[0.463, "o", "\u001b[?25l\b\u001b[m\u000f \b"]
[0.004, "o", "\u001b[1;2H#### hostapd configuration file ##############################################\r\n# Empty lines and lines starting with # are ignored\r\n\u001b[69X\u001b[4;3HAP netdevice name (without 'ap' postfix, i.e., wlan0 uses wlan0ap for    \u001b[5;3Hmanagement frames with the Host AP driver); wlan0 with many nl80211 drivers\u001b[6;3HNote: This attribute can be overridden by the values supplied with the '-i'\u001b[7;3Hcommand line parameter.\u001b[11X\r\ninterface=wlan0\u001b[35X\r\n\u001b[11X\n# In case of atheros and nl80211 driver interfaces, an additional\u001b[11;3Hconfiguration parameter, bridge, may be used to notify hostapd if the \u001b[12;3Hinterface is included in a bridge. This parameter is not used with Host AP\u001b[13;4Hriver. If the bridge parameter is not set, the drivers will automatically\u001b[14;3Hfigure out the bridge interface (assuming sysfs is enabled and mounted to\u001b[15;3H/sys) and this parameter may not be needed.\u001b[16;2H\u001b[77X\u001b[17;3HFor nl80211, this parameter can be used to request the AP interface to be\u001b[18;3Hadded to the bridge automatically (brctl may refuse to do this before hostapd\r\n# has been started to change the interface mode). If needed, the bridge\r\n# interface is also created.\u001b[21;2Hbridge=br0\u001b[68X\r\n\u001b[71X\u001b[23;3HDriver interface type (hostap/wired/none/nl80211/bsd);\u001b[19X\u001b[24;3Hdefault: hostap). nl80211 is used with all Linux mac80211 drivers.\u001b[25;3HUse driver=none if building hostapd as a standalone RADIUS server that does\u001b[26;2H not control any wireless/wired driver.\r\n# driver=hostap\r\n\u001b[74X\u001b[29;3HDriver interface parameters (mainly for development testing use)\u001b[12X\u001b[30;3Hdriver_params=<params>\u001b[47X\r\n\u001b[77X\u001b[32;3Hhostapd event logger configuration\u001b[33;2H\u001b[28X\r\n# Two output method: syslog and stdout (only usable if not forking to\u001b[35;3Hbackground).\u001b[59X\u001b[36;2H\u001b[77X\u001b[37;3HModule bitfield (ORed bitfield of modules that will be logged; -1 = all\u001b[38;3Hmodules):\u001b[66X\u001b[39;3Hbit 0 (1) = IEEE 802.11\u001b[40;2H bit 1 (2) = IEEE 802.1X\u001b[7X\r\n# bit 2 (4) = RADIUS\u001b[42;3Hbit \u001b[30m\u001b[103m3\u001b[m\u000f (8) = WPA\u001b[22X\u001b[43;3Hbit 4 (16) = driver interface\u001b[44;3Hbit 6 (64) = MLME\u001b[17X\u001b[45;2H\u001b[52X\u001b[46;3HLevels (minimum value for logged events):\u001b[47;4H0 = verbose debugging  \u001b[48;4H1 = debugging\u001b[61X\u001b[49;4H2 = informational messages\u001b[50;4H\u001b[30m\u001b[103m3\u001b[m\u000f = notification\u001b[36X\u001b[51;4H4 = warning\u001b[64X\u001b[52;2H\u001b[18X\r\nlogger_syslog=-1\r\nlogger_syslog_level=2\u001b[44X\r\nlogger_stdout=-1\u001b[56X\r\nlogger_stdout_level=2\r\n \u001b[58;3HInterface for separate control program. If this is specified, hostapd\u001b[59;2H will create this directory and a UNIX domain socket for listening to requests\u001b[60;2H from external programs (CLI/GUI, etc.) for status information and\u001b[61;2H configuration. The socket file will be named based on the interface name, so\u001b[62;2H multiple hostapd processes/interfaces can be run at the same time if more\u001b[63;3Hthan one interface is used.\u001b[29X\u001b[64;2H /run/hostapd is the recommended directory for sockets and by default,\u001b[65;3Hhostapd_cli will use it when trying to connect with hostapd.\u001b[66;223H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f42,7           Top\u001b[67;3H\u001b[?25h"]
[0.313, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001b[m\u000f4"]
[0.003, "o", "\u001b[1;2H This feature allows CAC to be run on dedicated radio RF chains while the\u001b[5X\u001b[2;3Hradio(s) are otherwise running normal AP activities on other channels.\r\n# This requires that the driver and the radio support it before feature will\u001b[4;3Hactually be enabled, i.e., this parameter value is ignored with drivers that\u001b[5;3Hdo not advertise support for the capability.\u001b[31X\u001b[6;3H0: Leave disabled (default)\u001b[48X\u001b[7;3H1: Enable it.\u001b[10X\r\n#enable_background_radar=1\u001b[10;3HSet minimum permitted max TX power (in dBm) for ACS and DFS channel selection.\u001b[11;3H(default 0, i.e., not constraint)\u001b[36X\u001b[12;2Hmin_tx_power=20\u001b[60X\r\n\u001b[76X\u001b[14;3HBeacon interval in kus (1.024 ms) (default: 100; range 15..65535)\u001b[8X\r\nbeacon_int=100\u001b[31X\r\n \u001b[17;3HDTIM (delivery traffic information message) period (range 1..255):\u001b[7X\u001b[18;3Hnumber of beacons between DTIMs (1 = every beacon includes DTIM element)\u001b[5X\u001b[19;3H(default: 2)\u001b[57X\r\ndtim_period=2\u001b[15X\r\n\u001b[11X\n# Maximum number of stations allowed in station table. New stations will be\u001b[23;3Hrejected after the station table is full. IEEE 802.11 has a limit of 2007\u001b[24;4Hifferent association IDs, so this number should not be larger than that.\u001b[25;3H(default: 2007)\u001b[60X\r\nmax_num_sta=255\u001b[25X\r\n\u001b[15X\n# RTS/CTS threshold; -1 = disabled (default); range -1..65535\u001b[29;3HIf this field is not included in hostapd.conf, hostapd will not control\u001b[30;3HRTS threshold and 'iwconfig wlan# rts <val>' can be used to set it.\r\nrts_threshold=-1\r\n\u001b[36X\u001b[33;2H Fragmentation threshold; -1 = disabled (default); range -1, 256..2\u001b[30m\u001b[103m34\u001b[m\u000f6\u001b[34;3HIf this field is not included in hostapd.conf, hostapd will not control\u001b[35;3Hfragmentation threshold and 'iwconfig wlan# frag <val>' can be used to set\u001b[36;2H it.\r\nfragm_threshold=-1\u001b[55X\r\n\u001b[11X\u001b[39;3HRate configuration\u001b[5X\u001b[40;3HDefault is to enable all rates supported by the hardware. This configuration\u001b[41;3Hitem allows this list be filtered so that only the listed rates will be left\u001b[42;3Hin the list. If the list is empty, all rates are used. This list can have\u001b[43;3Hentries that are not in the list of rates the hardware supports (such entries\u001b[44;3Hare ignored). The entries in this list are in 100 kbps, i.e., 11 Mbps = 110.\u001b[45;2H If this item is present, at least one rate have to be matching with the rates\u001b[46;3Hhardware supports.\u001b[23X\u001b[47;3Hdefault: use the most common supported rate setting for the selected\u001b[48;3Hhw_mode (i.e., this line can be removed from configuration file in most\u001b[49;3Hcases)\u001b[21X\u001b[50;2Hsupported_rates=10 20 55 110 60 90 120 180 240 360 480 540\r\n\u001b[14X\u001b[52;2H Basic rate set configuration\r\n# List of rates (in 100 kbps) that are included in the basic rate set.\r\n# If this item is not included, usually reasonable default set is used.\r\n#basic_rates=10 20\r\n#basic_rates=10 20 55 110\r\n#basic_rates=60 120 240\r\n\u001b[71X\u001b[59;3HBeacon frame TX rate configuration\u001b[43X\u001b[60;3HThis sets the TX rate that is used to transmit Beacon frames. If this item is\u001b[61;3Hnot included, the driver default rate (likely lowest rate) is used.\u001b[9X\u001b[62;3HLegacy (CCK/OFDM rates):\u001b[49X\u001b[63;3H   beacon_rate=<legacy rate in 100 kbps>\u001b[64;3HHT:\u001b[66X\u001b[65;3H   beacon_rate=ht:<HT MCS>\u001b[34X\u001b[66;223H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f261,69          6%\u001b[67;4H\u001b[?25h"]
[0.114, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001b[m\u000f0"]
[0.003, "o", "\u001b[1;2H#### hostapd configuration file ##############################################\u001b[2;3HEmpty lines and lines starting with # are ignored\u001b[21X\r\n\u001b[76X\u001b[4;3HAP netdevice name (without 'ap' postfix, i.e., wlan0 uses wlan0ap for\u001b[7X\u001b[5;3Hmanagement frames with the Host AP driver); wlan0 with many nl80211 drivers\u001b[6;3HNote: This attribute can be overridden by the values supplied with the '-i'\u001b[7;3Hcommand line parameter.\r\ninterface=wlan0\u001b[11X\u001b[10;3HIn case of atheros and nl80211 driver interfaces, an additional\u001b[15X\u001b[11;3Hconfiguration parameter, bridge, may be used to notify hostapd if the\u001b[12;2H interface is included in a bridge. This parameter is not used with Host AP\r\n# driver. If the bridge parameter is not set, the drivers will automatically\u001b[14;3Hfigure out the bridge interface (assuming sysfs is enabled and mounted to\r\n# /sys) and this parameter may not be needed.\r\n#\u001b[17;3HFor nl80211, this parameter can be used to request the AP interface to be\u001b[18;3Hadded to the bridge automatically (brctl may refuse to do this before hostapd\u001b[19;3Hhas been started to change the interface mode). If needed, the bridge\r\n# interface is also created.\r\n#bridge=br0\r\n\u001b[75X\u001b[23;3HDriver interface type (hostap/wired/none/nl80211/bsd);\u001b[19X\u001b[24;4Hefault: hostap). nl80211 is used with all Linux mac80211 drivers.\u001b[7X\u001b[25;3HUse driver=none if building hostapd as a standalone RADIUS server that does\r\n# not control any wireless/wired driver.\r\n# driver=hostap\r\n\u001b[61X\u001b[29;3HDriver interface parameters (mainly for development testing use)\u001b[7X\u001b[30;3Hdriver_params=<params>\u001b[45X\r\n\u001b[16X\n# hostapd event logger configuration\u001b[33;2H\u001b[70X\u001b[34;3HTwo output method: syslog and stdout (only usable if not forking to    \u001b[35;3Hbackground).\u001b[62X\u001b[36;2H    \r\n# Module bitfield (ORed bitfield of modules that will be logged; -1 = all\r\n# modules):\u001b[39;3Hbit 0 (1) = IEEE 802.11\u001b[40;3Hbit 1 (2) = IEEE 802.1X\u001b[53X\u001b[41;3Hbit 2 (4) = RADIUS\u001b[58X\u001b[42;3Hbit 3 (8) = WPA\u001b[58X\u001b[43;3Hbit 4 (16) = driver interface\u001b[48X\u001b[44;3Hbit 6 (64) = MLME\u001b[59X\u001b[45;2H\u001b[78X\u001b[46;3HLevels (minimum value for logged events):\u001b[47;3H 0 = verbose debugging\u001b[46X\u001b[48;3H 1 = debugging\u001b[57X\u001b[49;3H 2 = informational messages\u001b[50;2H  3 = notification\u001b[40X\r\n#  4 = warning\u001b[52;2H\u001b[29X\r\nlogger_syslog=-1\u001b[54X\r\nlogger_syslog_level=2\u001b[50X\r\nlogger_stdout=-1  \r\nlogger_stdout_level=2    \r\n\u001b[23X\n# Interface for separate control program. If this is specified, hostapd\u001b[59;3Hwill create this directory and a UNIX domain socket for listening to requests\u001b[60;3Hfrom external programs (CLI/GUI, etc.) for status information and\u001b[12X\u001b[61;3Hconfiguration. The socket file will be named based on the interface name, so\u001b[62;3Hmultiple hostapd processes/interfaces can be run at the same time if more\u001b[63;3Hthan one interface is used.\u001b[13X\u001b[64;3H/run/hostapd is the recommended directory for sockets and by default,\u001b[65;3Hhostapd_cli will use it when trying to connect with hostapd.\u001b[66;223H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f1,1            Top\u001b[67;5H\u001b[?25h"]
[0.130, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001b[m\u000f0"]
[0.004, "o", "\u001b[?25h"]
[2.329, "o", "\u001b[?25l\r\u001b[67;1H\u001b[?25h\u001b[?25l\u001b[?112c\u001b[?1002h\u001b[?1006h"]
[0.004, "o", "\u001b[91mE486: Pattern not found: 3400\u001b[H\u001b[?25h"]
[2.697, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001b[67;230H\u001b[m\u000fG\u001b[H\u001b[?25h"]
[0.003, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001b[67;230H \u001b[1;2H items, like channel)\u001b[57X\r\n\u001b[51X\n#bss=wlan0_1\u001b[4;2Hbssid=00:13:10:95:fe:0b\u001b[47X\u001b[5;3H...\u001b[72X\u001b[6;2H\u001b[76X\u001b[7;3HMultiple BSSID Advertisement in IEEE 802.11ax\r\n# IEEE Std 802.11ax-2021 added a feature where instead of multiple interfaces\r\n# on a common radio transmitting individual Beacon frames, those interfaces can\u001b[10;3Hform a set with a common Beacon frame transmitted for all. The interface\u001b[11;3Hwhich is brought up first is called the transmitting profile of the MBSSID\u001b[12;3Hset which transmits the Beacon frames. The remaining interfaces are called\u001b[13;3Hthe non-transmitting profiles and these are advertised inside the Multiple\u001b[14;3HBSSID element in the Beacon and Probe Response frames from the first\u001b[5X\u001b[15;3Hinterface.\u001b[33X\u001b[17;3HThe transmitting interface is visible to all stations in the vicinity, however\u001b[18;3Hthe stations that do not support parsing of the Multiple BSSID element will  \u001b[19;3Hnot be able to connect to the non-transmitting interfaces.\u001b[11X\u001b[20;2H\u001b[27X\n Enhanced Multiple BSSID Advertisements (EMA)\r\n# When enabled, the non-transmitting interfaces are split into multiple\u001b[23;3HBeacon frames. The number of Beacon frames required to cover all the\u001b[24;3Hnon-transmitting profiles is called the profile periodicity.\u001b[6X\u001b[25;2H\u001b[76X\u001b[26;3HRefer to IEEE Std 802.11-2020 for details regarding the procedure and\u001b[27;3Hrequired MAC address assignment.\r\n#\u001b[29;3HFollowing configuration is per radio.\u001b[27X\u001b[30;3H0 = Disabled (default)\r\n# 1 = Multiple BSSID advertisement enabled.\u001b[32;3H2 = Enhanced multiple BSSID advertisement enabled.\u001b[33;2Hmbssid=0\u001b[34;2H\u001b[68X\u001b[35;3HThe transmitting interface should be added with the 'interface' option while\u001b[36;2H the non-transmitting interfaces should be added using the 'bss' option.\u001b[37;3HSecurity configuration should be added separately per interface, if required.\u001b[38;2H\u001b[10X\u001b[39;3HExample:\u001b[15X\u001b[40;2Hmbssid=2\u001b[16X\u001b[41;2Hinterface=wlan2    \u001b[42;2Hctrl_interface=/run/hostapd\u001b[43;2Hwpa_passphrase=0123456789\u001b[5X\u001b[44;2Hieee80211w=2\u001b[6X\u001b[45;2Hsae_pwe=1\u001b[46;2Hauth_algs=1\u001b[31X\u001b[47;2Hwpa=2\u001b[18X\u001b[48;2Hwpa_pairwise=CCMP\u001b[49;2Hssid=<SSID-0>\u001b[15X\u001b[50;2Hbridge=br-lan\u001b[5X\u001b[51;2Hwpa_key_mgmt=SAE\u001b[52;2Hbssid=00:03:7f:12:84:84\r\n#\u001b[15X\r\n#bss=wlan2-1\u001b[9X\r\n#ctrl_interface=/run/hostapd\r\n#wpa_passphrase=0123456789\r\n#ieee80211w=2\u001b[58;2Hsae_pwe=1\u001b[61X\u001b[59;2Hauth_algs=1\u001b[67X\u001b[60;2Hwpa=2\u001b[61X\u001b[61;2Hwpa_pairwise=CCMP\u001b[60X\u001b[62;2Hssid=<SSID-1>\u001b[61X\u001b[63;2Hbridge=br-lan\u001b[15X\u001b[64;2Hwpa_key_mgmt=SAE\u001b[54X\u001b[65;2Hbssid=00:03:7f:12:84:85\u001b[38X\u001b[66;223H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f3383,1         Bot\r\u001b[A\u001b[?25h"]
